drew Watt (musician)|Watt]]\n* [[Sam Watters]]\n* [[Zedd]]\n| prev_title   = [[First Time (EP)|First Time]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n| name         = LP1\n| type         = studio\n| single1      = [[Strip That Down]]\n| single1date  = 19 May 2017\n| single2      = [[Get Low (Zedd and Liam Payne song)|Get Low]]\n| single2date  = 6 July 2017\n| single3      = [[Bedroom Floor]]\n| single3date  = 20 October 2017\n| single4      = [[Familiar (song)|Familiar]]\n| single4date  = 20 April 2018\n| single5      = [[Stack It Up]]\n| single5date  = 18 September 2019\n| single6      = [[All I Want (For Christmas)]]\n| single6date  = 25 October 2019\n| single7      = [[Live Forever (Liam Payne song)|Live Forever]]\n| single7date  = 6 December 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''LP1''''' is the debut studio album by English singer [[Liam Payne]], released on 6 December 2019 through [[Capitol Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://umusic.digital/lp1/|title=lp1 album pre-save + pre-add|website=umusic.digital|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> The album is [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]-orientated, drawing influence from [[Usher (musician)|Usher]] and [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref name=\"List\"/> \n\n''LP1'' includes the singles \"[[Strip That Down]]\" featuring [[Quavo]], \"[[Get Low (Zedd and Liam Payne song)|Get Low]]\" with [[Zedd]], \"[[Bedroom Floor]]\", \"[[Familiar (song)|Familiar]]\" with [[J Balvin]], \"[[Polaroid (Jonas Blue, Liam Payne and Lennon Stella song)|Polaroid]]\" with [[Jonas Blue]] and [[Lennon Stella]], \"[[Stack It Up]]\" featuring [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]], \"[[All I Want (For Christmas)]]\" and \"[[Live Forever (Liam Payne song)|Live Forever]]\" featuring [[Cheat Codes (DJs)|Cheat Codes]]. ''LP1'' debuted at number 17 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and number 111 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Background==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"I've had so many amazing experiences over the last few years which I've used as inspiration for this record -- it's been a real labor of love. I've worked with some incredibly talented people in the studio to produce an album that truly represents me which I'm very proud of\"\n| align = left\n| source = \u2014 Payne discussing the making of ''LP1''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8533515/liam-payne-debut-album-lp1-december|title=Christmas Just Came Early: Liam Payne Announces Release Date for 'LP1'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Pace|first=Lilly|date=18 October 2019|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n| width = 30%\n}}\nFollowing the release of his single \"[[Bedroom Floor]]\" in October 2017, Payne told [[Hits Radio]] that his album would be released in January 2018, saying he had worked with [[Ed Sheeran]] and that he \"didn't really want to nail [him]self down so there's some dark pop on there, some super urban tracks and a lot of [[trap music]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/hits-radio/entertainment/music/liam-payne-reveals-solo-album-release-date-can-expect/|title=Liam Payne reveals solo album release date and what we can expect|website=[[Hits Radio]]|date=20 October 2017|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> In May 2018, Payne told ''[[Good Morning America]]'' that the album was to be released on 14 September 2018, and that there was \"a good mix of beautiful people on my album, which is amazing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8456142/liam-payne-announces-album-release-date-interview-video|title=Liam Payne Reveals September Album Release Date, Hints at One Direction Reunion: Watch|work=Billboard|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|date=15 May 2018|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> However, in August 2018, Payne announced that he had delayed the release of the album and that he would be releasing his debut [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[First Time (EP)|First Time]]'' (2018) to make up for it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8470682/liam-payne-debut-ep-first-time|title=Liam Payne Announces Debut EP 'First Time'|work=Billboard|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=17 August 2018|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, following the release of \"[[Stack It Up]]\", [[MTV]] said Payne had \"spent much of 2019 in the studio\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3139470/liam-payne-stack-it-up-a-boogie-wit-da-hoodie/|title=Liam Payne's Crisp New 'Stack It Up' Is A Celebration Of Getting Paid|website=[[MTV]]|last=Hosken|first=Patrick|date=18 September 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> The same month, Payne revealed to Australian radio station [[Nova 96.9]] that the album was finished, that he was \"proud\" of it and it is \"exactly the way I'd want my first album to sound\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nova969.com.au/smallzy-s-surgery/liam-payne-says-his-debut-solo-album-finished|title=Liam Payne Says His Debut Solo Album Is Finished|website=[[Nova 96.9]]|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> He also stated that it is \"very [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]-orientated, with lots of artists that I like \u2013 an [[Usher (musician)|Usher]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] reference throughout\".<ref name=\"List\">{{cite web|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/111770-liam-paynes-solo-album-wont-come-out-until-2020/|title=Liam Payne's solo album won't come out until 2020|website=[[The List (magazine)|The List]]|date=28 September 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2019, Payne formally announced the album, its title and that it would be released on 6 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3wq0z7A5ua/|title=Liam Payne on Instagram: \"So I can finally reveal that my new album LP1 will be out on 6th December! I\u2019m so happy with it and I'm sorry it's taken longer than...\"|via=Instagram|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nPayne's debut single \"[[Strip That Down]]\" featuring [[Quavo]] serves as the album's lead single. Payne released \"[[Get Low (Zedd and Liam Payne song)|Get Low]]\" with [[Zedd]] as the album's second single on 6 July 2017. \"[[Bedroom Floor]]\" was released as the third single from the album on 20 October 2017. Payne's collaboration with [[J Balvin]] \"[[Familiar (song)|Familiar]]\" was released as the album's fourth single on 20 April 2018. \"[[Stack It Up]]\" featuring [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]] was released as the fifth single from the album on 16 September 2019. \"[[All I Want (For Christmas)]]\" was released as the album's sixth single on 25 October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8540134/liam-payne-new-song-all-i-want-for-christmas-announcement-teaser|title=All We Want for Christmas Is New Liam Payne Music & His New Song 'All I Want' Will Be an Early Gift|website=Billboard|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref> The song \"[[Live Forever (Liam Payne song)|Live Forever]]\" featuring electronic music DJ trio [[Cheat Codes (DJs)|Cheat Codes]] was released as the album's seventh single on 6 December 2019 along with the full album.\n\n===Other songs===\nThe album also includes the songs \"[[For You (Liam Payne and Rita Ora song)|For You (Fifty Shades Freed)]]\" with [[Rita Ora]] from the ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]'' soundtrack and \"[[Polaroid (Jonas Blue, Liam Payne and Lennon Stella song)|Polaroid]]\" with [[Jonas Blue]] and [[Lennon Stella]] from Blue's debut studio album ''[[Blue (Jonas Blue album)|Blue]]''.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 44/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/lp1/liam-payne|title=LP1 by Liam Payne Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lp1-mw0003328452|title=LP1 \u2013 Liam Payne {{!}} Songs Reviews, Credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Yeung|first=Neil Z.|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Evening Standard]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"guardianreview\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[i (newspaper)|i]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"inews.co.uk\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/liam-payne-review-lp1-album-tracklist-stream-cheryl-one-direction-a9233971.html|title=Liam Payne review \u2013 LP1: From One Direction to One Dimensional|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=6 December 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"nmereview\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 4.3/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/liam-payne-lp1/|title=Liam Payne: LP1 Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Kameir|first=Rawiya|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"timesreview\"/>\n}}\n''LP1'' received mixed to negative reviews. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalised rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has an average score of 44 out of 100, which indicates \"mixed or average reviews\" based on seven reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> It was the worst reviewed album with seven reviews or more of 2019 on the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-released-in-2019|title=Best Albums of 2019|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=20 December 2019|accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHelen Brown of ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote \"he's got a nice set of pipes. He gets the songs across. But without imposing any personality on them he's just, well, a singing six-pack\" and that \"it's all fine: shiny and efficient pop, smelling of body oil and new car upholstery. But Payne treats each track like a rental car. He gives each song a spin and hands the keys back like a good lad without leaving a trace,\" ending the review by stating \"he's gone from One Direction to One Dimensional\".<ref name=\"Independent\"/> Mark Kennedy, writing for [[ABC News]], called the album \"embarassing\" while writing that the album \"never really gets off the ground, a collection of monotonous club songs that often sound like warmed-over [[Justin Bieber]] rejects.\" He further criticised Payne's decision to add \"offerings [that] are more than two years old\" and the fact that Payne only co-wrote four songs, although he did compliment \"[[Stack It Up]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/review-liam-payne-stumbles-badly-embarrassing-debut-cd-67545246|title=Review: Liam Payne stumbles badly with embarrassing debut CD|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[ABC News]]|last=Kennedy|first=Mark|date=7 December 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> Laura Snapes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' opined that it is a \"terrible pop album, but very effective contraception\".<ref name=\"guardianreview\"/> Michael Cragg, also of ''The Guardian'', called the album \"genre-ticking anonymity\" and \"occasionally painful yet weirdly Payne-less.\"<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/dec/08/liam-payne-lp1-review</ref> El Hunt of ''[[NME]]'' felt Payne was \"so focused on ticking boxes that he forgets to have fun\" and that it \"shows a more grown-up side to the former One Direction member, and cherry-picks from pretty much every genre that's in vogue right now. The problem is that it doesn't tell us much about Liam Payne\" while particularly talking down on \"Both Ways\". Hunt did, however, note that the album \"can be fun when it does loosen up a little more\", naming \"[[Familiar (song)|Familiar]]\", \"Heart Meet Break\", and \"[[Bedroom Floor]]\" as standout tracks.<ref name=\"nmereview\"/> Rawiya Kameir of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' was critical, calling Payne \"another pop star flailing to find his identity amid trend-hopping production and half-baked lyrics\" and that \"listening to LP1, you almost feel sorry for Payne. It\u2019s maybe more pathetic to have failed not for risking too much, but after seeming to have tried so little.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n\nNeil Z. Yeung of [[AllMusic]] wrote that Payne \"tackles hip-hop and electronic genres but struggles to distinguish himself from the crop of similar-sounding contemporaries\" and that a majority of the songs \"sound more like a streaming playlist set to shuffle\" while adding that the album is \"front-loaded with mostly forgettable trifles\" and \"saved by this bountiful back-end, which plays like an early prediction of a potential greatest-hits collection\" while advising Payne to \"find a more distinctive vision and a team who can better utilize his strong vocals.\" Yeung also added that the album's best tracks include featured artists, particuraly praising \"[[For You (Liam Payne and Rita Ora song)|For You]]\" as the album's best track while also complimenting \"Familiar\", \"[[Get Low (Zedd and Liam Payne song)|Get Low]]\", and \"Stack It Up\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Writing for ''[[The Times]]'', Will Hodgkinson called the album \"dull\" but praised Payne's \"strong voice\".<ref name=\"timesreview\"/> A.D. Amorosi, writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', opined that \"the writing and singing aren't strong enough and come across as C-level [[Justin Timberlake|Timberlake]] material\" while ending the review by saying \"during \"Home with You,\" one of Payne's better singles not included on this album, the singer claims: \"Too many cooks in the kitchen / Too many fools here listening / Why don't we find somewhere quiet, quiet.\" Liam Payne should have taken his own advice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/album-reviews/liam-payne-lp1-album-review-1203427388/|title=Liam Payne's 'LP1': Album Review|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Amorosi|first=A.D.|date=6 December 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> Lauren Murphy of ''[[entertainment.ie]]'' called the songs \"indistinguishable\" and the album \"a wasted opportunity\" and \"dull\", noting that the album \"sounds like a collection of songs \u2013 not a cohesive album\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.ie/music/first-impressions-a-track-by-track-review-of-liam-paynes-debut-album-lp1-432571/|title=First Impressions: A track-by-track review of Liam Payne's debut album 'LP1'|website=[[entertainment.ie]]|last=Murphy|first=Lauren|date=6 December 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> Thomas Green, writing for the ''[[i (newspaper)|i]]'', stated that \"[[One Direction]]'s devoted fans will love this, but nobody else will\" while commenting that the album \"should make lots of money. Not much else about it seems to matter to Payne.\" He also opioned that the second half of the album, \"stacked with tunes he's released over the last three years\" is \"more enjoyable\" than the newer releases.<ref name=\"inews.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe album specifically received heavy criticism from critics and the general public for fetishising bisexual women in the track \"Both Ways\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-50705346|title=Liam Payne 'reinforcing stereotypes' about bi women|work=[[BBC News]]|date=8 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/liam-payne-both-ways-bisexuality-album-harry-styles-a9236811.html|title=Liam Payne's new song has been condemned for 'fetishising bisexuality'|work=[[The Independent]]|last=White|first=Adam|date=7 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/fans-accuse-liam-payne-fetishizing-bisexuality-new-song-both-ways|title=Fans Are Accusing Liam Payne of Fetishizing Bisexuality With His Song \"Both Ways\"|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|last=Elizabeth|first=De|date=7 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome reviews were more positive, with Rachel McGrath of the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' opining that Payne \"finds the perfect middle ground\" and writing that the album is \"perfectly packaged hits that see him reaffirm his love for hip-hop, dabble with reggaeton and even croon a Christmas track.\"<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> Markos Papadatos of the ''Digital Journal'' penned that the album was \"incredible\", calling it \"worth the wait\" and \"all heart and soul, and it is highly recommended for all.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-liam-payne-releases-amazing-breakthrough-studio-album-lp1/article/563088|title=Review: Liam Payne releases amazing breakthrough studio album 'LP1'|work=Digital Journal|last=Papadatos|first=Markos|date=6 December 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from [[Apple Music]].<ref name=\"Apple Music\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/album/1483034493|title=LP1 by Liam Payne|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 54:35\n| title1 = [[Stack It Up]]\n| note1 = featuring [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Ed Sheeran|Edward Sheeran]]|[[A Boogie wit da Hoodie|Artist Dubose]]|[[Steve Mac|Steve McCutcheon]]|[[Fred Again|Frederik Gibson]]}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|[[Steve Mac]]|Gibson}}\n| length1 = 2:45\n| title2 = Remember\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[James Abrahart]]|Jonathan Price|[[The Monsters & Strangerz|Stefan Johnson]]|[[The Monsters & Strangerz|Jordan Johnson]]|[[The Monsters & Strangerz|Marcus Lomax]]|Oliver Peterhof}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|[[The Monsters & Strangerz]]|German}}\n| length2 = 3:09\n| title3 = Heart Meet Break\n| writer3 = {